[[Image:Mafia family structure tree.en.svg|thumb|350px|Italian mafia family structure tree]]

A '''capodecina''' (literally 'head of ten',<ref name=schneider83>Schneider, ''Reversible Destiny'', p. 83</ref> also called [[caporegime]] in the [[American Mafia]]) is the head of a decina, a branch within a [[Sicilian Mafia|Mafia]] family. In the larger families, a capodecina is selected by the head of the family and coordinates units of about ten people.<ref name=paoli41>Paoli, ''Mafia Brotherhoods'', p. 41</ref>

Mafia members are organized under the supervision of a capodecina who reports to the [[capo famiglia]], the head of the Mafia family or [[cosca]]. The term derives from ''dieci'' (ten), suggesting that each would be in charge of ten men.<ref name=gambetta111>Gambetta, ''The Sicilian Mafia'', p. 111</ref> The term was mentioned as early as the 1880s in Sicily to describe the organisation of the [[Fratellanza]], a Mafia-type organisation in [[Agrigento]], in the south of [[Sicily]].<ref name=gambetta294>Gambetta, ''The Sicilian Mafia'', p. 294</ref>

The Mafioso [[Melchiorre Allegra]] spoke of a "capo della decina" in his 1937 testimony. He said a family split into groups of ten men each when it became unmanageably large.<ref name=gambetta294/><ref>Twentyfive pages of Allegra’s testimony were published in 1962 in the newspaper ''[[L'Ora]]'' by [[Mauro De Mauro]]. See: [http://www.exlegi.ox.ac.uk/resources/allegra.asp Testimony of Melchiorre Allegra] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120320184154/http://www.exlegi.ox.ac.uk/resources/allegra.asp |date=2012-03-20 }}, ExLEGI website</ref>

