'''Darrell Lane Castle''' (born October 11, 1948) is an American politician and attorney from [[Memphis, Tennessee]]. He was the [[Constitution Party (United States)|Constitution Party]]'s nominee for [[Vice President of the United States]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]] and for [[President of the United States|President]] in the [[United States presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential election]].<ref name="CastleIsVP">{{cite web|url=http://www.ballot-access.org/2008/04/26/darrell-castle-is-constitution-party-vice-presidential-nominee|title=Darrell Castle is Constitution Party Vice-Presidential Nominee|last=Winger|first=Richard|date=April 26, 2008|publisher=''[[Ballot Access News]]''|accessdate=November 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name="CastleIsPrez">{{cite web|url=http://www.independentpoliticalreport.com/2016/04/darrell-castle-wins-the-constitution-partys-presidential-nomination/|title=Darrell Castle wins the Constitution Party’s presidential nomination|last=Lesiak|first=Krzyszof|date=April 16, 2016|publisher=Independent Political Report|accessdate=April 16, 2016}}</ref> As the presidential nominee, Castle received 202,348 votes, and placed sixth nationwide.

==Early life and education==
Castle grew up in [[Kingsport, Tennessee]]. He attended Ketron High School and [[East Tennessee State University]] (ETSU), graduating in 1966 and 1970, respectively.  At ETSU, he earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] degree, double-majoring in [[political science]] and [[history]].

Castle then became a commissioned officer in the [[United States Marine Corps|U.S. Marine Corps]], serving for four years and attaining the rank of first lieutenant.<ref name="ConstitutionParty1">{{cite web|url=http://www.constitutionparty.com/news.php?aid=365 |title=As Veterans Day Approaches, the Constitution Party salutes its own and all Americans who have served in our nation’s military forces! |date=November 10, 2006 |publisher=Constitution Party National Committee |accessdate=November 12, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113033357/http://www.constitutionparty.com/news.php?aid=365 |archivedate=November 13, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>  After his discharge, he returned to ETSU and began his graduate study of history.  He then attended the law school at [[University of Memphis|Memphis State University]] and earned a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 1979.

Castle has served as a deacon and deacon chairman in his local church.<ref name=":2">{{cite web|url=http://www.castlereport.us/who-is-darrell-castle|title=Who is Darrell Castle?|website=The Castle Report|accessdate=April 25, 2016}}</ref> In 1998, he and his wife founded Mia’s Children Foundation, a Christian mission in Bucharest, Romania which ministers to homeless Romani children.<ref name=":2"/>

==Law career==
Upon receiving his law degree in [[Memphis, Tennessee|Memphis]], Castle became an attorney. In 1984, he opened a private firm which later grew into Darrell Castle and Associates. Since then, Castle has opened firms in [[Milwaukee]], [[Detroit]], and [[Kansas City, Missouri]]. His firms focus on consumer bankruptcy and personal injury, but also represent clients in the areas of social security, disability, and workers' compensation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darrellcastle.com/|title=Memphis Bankruptcy Attorneys & Personal Injury Lawyers|website=darrellcastle.com|accessdate=April 24, 2016}}</ref>

==Political involvement==
{{moresources|section|date=November 2016}}
At the [[2008 Constitution Party National Convention]] in [[Kansas City, Missouri]], [[Baptist]] pastor [[Chuck Baldwin]] defeated former [[Assistant Secretary of State for International Organization Affairs]] [[Alan Keyes]] to win the party's nomination. The party then nominated Castle to the ticket as its vice presidential candidate. Baldwin had been the Constitution Party nominee for Vice President in 2004.

At the [[2012 Constitution Party National Convention]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], Castle declared his candidacy for the party's presidential nomination one day prior to the nomination vote, citing requests from several delegates that he seek the nomination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentpoliticalreport.com/2012/04/news-flash-darrell-castle-to-seek-constitution-party-nomination/|title=NEWS FLASH: Darrell Castle to Seek Constitution Party Nomination|date=April 20, 2012|work=Independent Political Report}}</ref> He finished as runner-up to former United States Congressman [[Virgil Goode]], who won the nomination on the first ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentpoliticalreport.com/2012/04/virgil-goode-wins-constitution-party-nomination-on-first-ballot-picks-vp-choice/|title=Virgil Goode Wins Constitution Party Nomination on First Ballot, Picks VP Choice|date=April 21, 2012|work=Independent Political Report}}</ref>

Castle is the former National Vice-Chairman of the Constitution Party.

===2016 presidential campaign===
{{Main article|Darrell Castle presidential campaign, 2016}}
{{US 2016 presidential elections series}}
Castle was a candidate for the Constitution Party's 2016 presidential nomination, but withdrew his candidacy in January 2016 because of unspecified health concerns.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://ballot-access.org/2016/01/06/darrell-castle-withdraws-from-constitution-party-presidential-nomination-race|title=Darrell Castle Withdraws from Constitution Party Presidential Nomination Race|publisher=Ballot Access News|date=January 6, 2016|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> However, on the eve of the 2016 nominating convention, [[Richard Winger]] of ''[[Ballot Access News]]'' reported that Castle had re-entered the nomination process.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ballot-access.org/2016/04/12/joe-miller-decides-not-to-seek-constitution-party-presidential-nomination/|title=Joe Miller Decides Not to Seek Constitution Party Presidential Nomination|website=ballot-access.org|publisher=Ballot Access News|date=April 12, 2016|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>

On April 16, 2016, Castle secured the presidential nomination for the Constitution Party.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=http://www.mwcnews.net/news/americas/58393-constitution-party-candidate.html|title=US: Darrell Castle named Constitution Party candidate|last=Agencies|website=www.mwcnews.net|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref>  He vowed, if elected, to get the United States out of the [[United Nations]] and [[NATO]].<ref name=":0"/> "Our borders are worth defending. If we can secure the borders of Korea and Germany, then we can secure the borders of the United States", said Castle.<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=http://www.good4utah.com/news/local-news/the-constitution-party-hosts-national-convention-in-salt-lake-city|title=The Constitution Party hosts national convention in Salt Lake City|last=Mills|first=Glen|website=GOOD4UTAH|language=en-US|access-date=April 24, 2016}}</ref> He made no reference to previous health concerns.<ref name=":1"/>

Castle's campaign received endorsements from [[Chuck Baldwin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://castle2016.com/what-people-are-saying|title=Endorsements|publisher=Castle 2016.com|accessdate=August 24, 2016}}</ref> [[Glenn Beck]] and the [[Georgia Right to Life]] [[Political action committee|PAC]].<ref>[http://grtlpac.org/pac-endorsements "Endorsements – GRTL PAC"], Georgia Right to Life PAC; retrieved July 2, 2016.</ref>

As of June 30, 2016, Castle had raised $10,289.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fec.gov/fecviewer/CandidateCommitteeDetail.do?candidateCommitteeId=P60021102&tabIndex=1|title=Committee/Candidate Details|publisher=Fec.gov|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>

====Opinion polls====
Castle's campaign saw only limited inclusion in opinion polls. Some state polls found a level of support between 1% and 3%.{{fact|date=September 2016}}

==Political positions==
{{moresources|section|date=November 2016}}
In an interview with ''Liberty Hangout'', Castle has said he is more [[libertarian]] than 2016 [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]] [[2016 Libertarian National Convention|presidential nominee]] [[Gary Johnson]].<ref name=LH>{{cite web|url=http://libertyhangout.org/2016/07/interview-with-darrell-castle-constitution-candidate|title=Constitution Party Candidate, Darrell Castle, Says He's More Libertarian Than Gary Johnson|publisher=Liberty Hangout|date=July 2, 2016|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> 

He describes himself as [[pro-life]],<ref name=LH/> and opposes federal funding of [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://castle2016.com/platform/ |title=Campaign Platform |publisher=Castle 2016 |date=April 16, 2016 |accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref> Castle supports funding of space exploration.<ref name=ISW>{{cite web|url=http://www.isidewith.com |title=I Side With |publisher=I Side With| date=June 12, 2016 |accessdate=August 26, 2016}}</ref> He opposes the [[war on drugs]].<ref name=LH/> When it comes to [[prostitution]], [[gambling]], [[smoking]], polygamous relationships, or any other activities made by consenting adults, Castle says he sees no role for the federal government to get involved.<ref name=LH/> He wants decriminalization of cannabis use, however opposes full legalization.<ref name=ISW/> He favors securing the borders.<ref name=LH/>  He has described his foreign policy views as [[Non-interventionism|non-interventionist]].<ref name=LH/> He favors the United States withdrawing from the [[United Nations]], [[NATO]], [[Trans-Pacific Partnership|TPP]], [[North American Free Trade Agreement|NAFTA]], [[Dominican Republic-Central America Free Trade Agreement|CAFTA-DR]], [[General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade|GATT]], and [[World Trade Organization|WTO]]. He favors ending the [[Federal Reserve System|Federal Reserve]].<ref name=LH/>

On June 12, 2016, Castle directly indicated a number of his political positions on the website iSideWith, which seeks to match voters with the candidates whose positions most closely match users' policy preferences as determined by a multiple-choice survey.<ref name=ISW/> Castle presents himself as [[Gun politics in the United States|pro-gun]] and pro-[[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]], indicating that he believes there should not be "more restrictions on the current process of purchasing a gun" and is against banning individuals on the [[no-fly list]] from "purchasing guns and ammunition." 

While being completely opposed to it morally, Castle explicitly indicated that [[same-sex marriage]] is among the consensual activities in which he believes the government should not be involved. He opposes [[Vaccination policy#Compulsory vaccination|compulsory vaccination]], and has endorsed the requirement of [[GMO labeling]], stating that "people have a right to know what is in their food". He is against [[Common Core State Standards Initiative|Common Core]] standards. He believes that felons should be [[Felony disenfranchisement|allowed to vote]], "but only after completing their sentences or parole/probation". He favors photographic [[Voter ID laws in the United States|voter identification requirements]] as a means of preventing voter fraud. Castle has expressed opposition to the retirement of [[solitary confinement]] for juvenile prisoners, on the grounds that the practice "is necessary for violent criminals who are a danger to themselves and other inmates". He believes that constitutional rights extend to foreign nationals suspected of terrorism, but only "inside the United States and not abroad".{{cn|date=November 2016}}

Castle believes "physically and mentally capable adults on [[welfare]]" should be required to work. However, he opposes drug tests for welfare recipients as an infringement of privacy. He has expressed opposition to any government regulation of employee compensation by private businesses. He does not believe that [[Illegal immigration to the United States|illegal immigrants]] should have access to government healthcare or [[Tuition payments#College tuition for undocumented students|in-state tuition rates]]. He is against the [[Affordable Care Act]]. He opposes governmental [[environmental law|environmental regulations]].{{cn|date=November 2016}}

Castle opposes [[Term limits in the United States|term limits]] for members of Congress, believing that elections suffice to test the effectiveness of officeholders.<ref name=ISW/>

