'''John Langdon''' (June 26, 1741{{spaced ndash}}September 18, 1819) was a politician from [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]], and a [[Founding Father of the United States]]. He served as a delegate to the [[Philadelphia Convention|Constitutional Convention]], signed the [[United States Constitution]], and was one of the first two [[United States senator]]s from that state.

As a member of the [[Continental Congress]] Langdon was an early supporter of the [[American Revolutionary War|Revolutionary War]]. He later served in [[United States Congress]] for 12 years, including as the first [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate|president pro tempore]] of the Senate, before becoming [[governor of New Hampshire]]. He turned down a nomination for [[Vice President of the United States|Vice Presidential]] candidate in 1812.

==Biography==
===Early years===
Langdon's father was a prosperous farmer and local ship builder whose family had emigrated to America before 1660 from [[Sheviock]], [[Caradon]], [[Cornwall]].  The Langdons were among the first to settle near the mouth of the [[Piscataqua River]], a settlement which became [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth]], one of [[New England]]'s major [[seaport]]s. Langdon attended the local grammar school run by a veteran of the 1745 [[Siege of Louisbourg (1745)|Siege of Louisbourg]] against the [[France|French]] at [[Fortress Louisbourg]] in [[New France]]. After finishing his primary education, he served an [[apprentice]]ship as a clerk. He and his older brother, [[Woodbury Langdon]], rejected the opportunity to join pop in their father's successful agricultural livelihood and apprenticed themselves to local naval merchants instead.

===To sea===
By age 22, Langdon was [[Captain (nautical)|captain]] of a [[cargo ship]] called the ''Andromache,'' sailing to the [[West Indies]]. Four years later he owned his first [[Cargo ship|merchantman]], and would continue over time to acquire a small fleet of vessels engaging in the [[triangular trade#New England|triangle trade]] between Portsmouth, the [[Caribbean Sea|Caribbean]], and [[London]].{{citation needed|date=December 2016}} His older brother was even more successful in international trade, and by 1777 both young men were among Portsmouth's wealthiest citizens.

===As revolutionary===
British control of the shipping industries greatly hurt Langdon's business, motivating him to become a vigorous and prominent supporter of the revolutionary movement in the 1770s. He served on the New Hampshire [[Committee of Correspondence]] and a nonimportation committee, and also attended various [[Patriot (American Revolution)|Patriot]] assemblies. In 1774, he participated in the seizure and confiscation of British [[munition]]s from [[Fort William and Mary]].

Langdon served as a member of the [[Second Continental Congress]] from 1775 to 1776. He resigned in June 1776 to become agent for the Continental forces against the [[Kingdom of Great Britain|British]] and superintended the construction of several warships including the ''[[USS Raleigh (1776)|Raleigh]]'', the ''[[USS America (1782)|America]]'', and the ''[[USS Ranger (1777)|Ranger]]'', which was captained by [[John Paul Jones]]. In 1777, he equipped an expedition against the British, participating in the [[Battle of Bennington]] and commanding [[Langdon's Company of Light Horse Volunteers]] at [[Battle of Saratoga|Saratoga]] and in [[Battle of Rhode Island|Rhode Island]].

===Founding father===
[[Image:Portsmouth, NH - Governor John Langdon House.JPG|thumb|left|[[Governor John Langdon House]], Portsmouth, New Hampshire]]
In 1784 he built at Portsmouth the mansion now known as the [[Governor John Langdon House]]. Langdon was elected to two terms as [[Governor of New Hampshire#History|President of New Hampshire]], once between 1785 and 1786 and again between 1788 and 1789. He was a member of the [[Congress of the Confederation]] in 1787 and became a delegate to the [[Constitutional Convention (United States)|Constitutional Convention]] in 1787, serving as a member of the New Hampshire delegation. Langdon was elected to the U.S. Senate and served from March 4, 1789 to March 3, 1801. He was elected the first President pro tempore of the Senate on April 6, 1789, and also served as president pro tempore during the second Congress.

During the 1787 constitutional debates in Philadelphia, Langdon spoke out against [[James Madison]]'s proposed "negative" on state laws simply because he felt that should the Senate be granted this power and not the House of Representatives, it would "hurt the feelings" of House members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avalon.law.yale.edu/18th_century/debates_710.asp|title=Avalon Project – Madison Debates – July 10|publisher=|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>{{Dubious|date=November 2013}}

In 1798, Langdon assisted [[Oney Judge]] to evade [[Burwell Bassett]],  the nephew of [[George Washington|George and]] [[Martha Washington]], who had intended to kidnap Judge and return her to slavery with the Washingtons.<ref name=Gerson>[http://seacoastnh.com/blackhistory/ona.html Eva Gerson, "Ona Judge Staines: Escape from Washington"], 2000, ''Black History'', SeacoastNH</ref>

===New Hampshire statesman===
Langdon later served as a member of the [[New Hampshire Legislature]] (1801–05), with the last two terms as [[speaker (politics)|speaker]]; he served as [[governor of New Hampshire|governor]] from 1805 to 1812, except for a year between 1809 and 1810. In 1808, his niece, Catherine Whipple Langdon, married [[Edmund Roberts (diplomat)#Early life|Edmund Roberts]].<ref>{{cite web |url=  http://www.accessgenealogy.com/scripts/data/database.cgi?file=Data&report=SingleArticle&ArticleID=0001473 |title=  Calvin Howard Bell Family |author=   |authorlink=   |date=  April 23, 2012 |format=   |work=  extract from Bell Family History |publisher=  Access Genealogy |accessdate=  April 19, 2012 |quote=  Judge Woodbury Langdon, of Portsmouth, N. H.; Delegate to the Continental Congress, 1779; President of N. H. Senate, 1784; Judge of the Superior Court of N. H., 1782–91....(a) Catherine Whipple Langdon: m. 1808, Edmund Roberts, of Portsmouth, N. H. |deadurl=  yes |archiveurl=  https://web.archive.org/web/20111104133817/http://www.accessgenealogy.com/scripts/data/database.cgi?file=Data&report=SingleArticle&ArticleID=0001473 |archivedate=  November 4, 2011 |df=  mdy-all }}</ref> Langdon declined the nomination to be a candidate for [[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] with James Madison in 1812, and later retired.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} He died in Portsmouth in 1819 and was interred at the Langdon Tomb in the [[List of New Hampshire Historical Markers: 101-125|North Cemetery]].<ref>New Hampshire History Marker #114</ref>

===Legacy===
The town of [[Langdon, New Hampshire]] is named after him,<ref>{{cite book|last=Gannett|first=Henry|title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9V1IAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA181|year=1905|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|page=181}}</ref> as well as Langdon Street in [[Madison, Wisconsin]], a town with numerous streets named after founding fathers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/odd/archives/002071.asp|title=Wisconsin Historical Society|publisher=|accessdate=July 30, 2016}}</ref>

