{{More footnotes|date=October 2015}}
'''Dr Dame Julia Margaret Polak''', [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]], [[Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]] (26 June 1939 – 11 August 2014)<ref name=Obituary>{{cite web|title=Professor Dame Julia Polak - obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/11082090/Professor-Dame-Julia-Polak-obituary.html|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=8 September 2014|date=8 September 2014}}</ref> was an Argentine-born British pathologist. She was head of the Centre for Tissue Engineering and Regenerative Medicine at [[Imperial College London]], a centre for medical research she set up with Larry Hench, also from Imperial College, to develop cells and tissues for transplantation into humans.
==Personal life== Julia Polak was born in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]]. She was educated at the [[University of Buenos Aires]], before moving to London. She was married to a fellow academic, and had three children.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}
==Career== Polak was one of the longest surviving recipients of a heart and lung transplant in the [[United Kingdom]]. It was her transplant in 1995 which caused her to change her career direction from [[pathology]] towards the newly developing field of [[tissue engineering]].
She was editor of the journal, ''Tissue Engineering'', as well as a member of the MRC/UK Stem Cell Bank Clinical and User Liaison Committee and an advisor to the Science and Parliament Committees. She was recognized as one of the most highly cited and influential researchers in her field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://highlycited.com/categories/clinical_medicine/|title=Clinical Medicine category list|work=[[ISIHighlyCited.com]]|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref>
Her work was recognized by the Society for Endocrinology, the International Academy of Pathology and the Association of Clinical Pathologists. She received funding through the Texas/United Kingdom Collaborative Research Initiative in Biosciences. {{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}
==Honours== She was named in the Queen's Birthday Honours List 2003 and was made [[List of Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] for her services to medicine. In 2004 she received the [[Ellison-Cliffe Lecture|Ellison-Cliffe Medal]] from the [[Royal Society of Medicine]].
==Death== Dr Dame Julia Polak died on 11 August 2014, aged 75, from undisclosed causes.<ref name=Obituary/>
